# Intuition
The intuition behind this approach is that we want to fill the bags with the least remaining capacity first, as adding rocks to those bags will result in the maximum increase in the number of bags with full capacity.

# Approach

Here is the step-by-step approach:

- Initialize a priority queue called helper with the greater<int> comparator.
- Iterate over the bags and calculate the difference between the capacity and the current number of rocks in each bag. Push these differences into the helper priority queue.
- Initialize a counter variable to keep track of the number of bags at full capacity.
    - While the helper priority queue is not empty and we have additional rocks to place (trocks >= 0), do the following:
    - Increment the counter variable to count a bag with full capacity.
    - Get the top element from the helper priority queue, which represents the bag with the smallest remaining capacity.
    - Remove the top element from the helper priority queue.
    - Subtract the remaining capacity from trocks.
- If trocks is still greater than or equal to 0, it means we have additional rocks left but no bags to fill. In this case, return the total number of bags (rocks.size()).
- Otherwise, return counter - 1, which represents the maximum number of bags with full capacity.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
 O(nlogn)

- Space complexity:
 O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumBags(vector<int>& capacity, vector<int>& rocks, int trocks) {
        priority_queue<int,vector<int>,greater<int>>helper;
        for(int i=0;i<rocks.size();i++)
        {
            helper.push(capacity[i]-rocks[i]);
        }
        int counter=0;
        while(!helper.empty() && trocks>=0)
        {
            counter++;
            int t=helper.top();
            helper.pop();
            trocks-=t;

        }
        if(trocks>=0)
        return rocks.size();
        return counter-1;
    }
};
```

