solutions.content:
The first version's best time was 14ms. The second one 23ms. And the 3rd one gets around 14ms.

Of the three, I think the 3rd is the best as it requires only one pass over the data.

## Approach
The `capacity` vector is updated to reflect the remaining space of each bag after subtracting the number of rocks in each bag. The vector is sorted ascending. `capacity` is then iterated over (skipping all bags with 0 capacity), subtracting each item's remaining space from `additional` (the remaining rocks). When `additional` dips below 0, counting stops.

## Complexity
- Time: $$O(n*log(n))$$
- Space: $$O(1)$$ *auxiliary* space.

```rust
impl Solution {
    pub fn maximum_bags(capacity         : Vec<i32>, 
                        rocks            : Vec<i32>, 
                        additional_rocks : i32) 
        -> i32 
    {
        let mut additional = additional_rocks;
        let mut capacity   = capacity;

        capacity.iter_mut().zip(rocks).for_each(|(c, r)| *c -= r);
        capacity.sort_unstable();

        let start = capacity.partition_point(|&n| n < 1);

        capacity[start..].into_iter()
                         .take_while(|&n| { additional -= n; additional >= 0 })
                         .count() as i32
        + start as i32
    }
}
```

## Using BinaryHeap

`BinaryHeap::from(capacity)` in the code below doesn't allocate more space; it takes the vector and assigns it to the `BinaryHeap`'s internal data field. The capacity values have inverted sign due to `BinaryHeap` being a max heap.

## Complexity
- Time: $$O(n*log(n))$$
- Space: $$O(1)$$ *auxiliary* space.

```rust
use std::collections::BinaryHeap;

impl Solution {
    pub fn maximum_bags(capacity         : Vec<i32>, 
                        rocks            : Vec<i32>, 
                        additional_rocks : i32) 
        -> i32 
    {
        let     n          = rocks.len();
        let mut capacity   = capacity;
        let mut additional = additional_rocks;

        capacity.iter_mut().zip(rocks).for_each(|(c, r)| *c = r - *c);

        let mut capacity = BinaryHeap::from(capacity);

        (0..n).filter_map(|_| capacity.pop())
              .take_while(|&n| { additional += n; additional >= 0 })
              .count() as i32
    }
}
```

## Single Pass Over Data

This version only takes one single pass over the data set to find the answer. Both of the examples above take multiple passes over it either explicitly, or implicitly.

As the input data is cycled over, the unfilled capacity of the current bag is used as the heap key. Bags are added until we have enough on the heap to eat up all the `additional_rocks`. Then we continue.

Bags that have more left over capacity are going to eat up `additional_rocks` faster. So those are at the top of the heap, ready to be tossed out for better options. When a bag comes along that has less free capacity than the heap's top item, it bumps the largest bag off the heap before bing pushed. This strategy ensures the heap will be populated by the bags with the least additional capacity when the cycle completes.

## Complexity
- Time: $$O(n*log(n))$$ The performance may be better than this since pop operations aren't performed for every item. The heap's pop operation is $$O(log(n))$$. Other operations are $$O(1)$$.
- Space: $$O(n)$$ This is probably actually `O(min(additional_rocks, n))`

```rust
use std::collections::BinaryHeap;

impl Solution {
    pub fn maximum_bags(capacity         : Vec<i32>, 
                        rocks            : Vec<i32>, 
                        additional_rocks : i32) 
        -> i32 
    {
        let     n    = rocks.len();
        let mut sum  = 0;
        let mut heap = BinaryHeap::new();

        for i in 0..n {
            let diff = capacity[i] - rocks[i];

            if diff + sum <= additional_rocks {
                heap.push(diff);
                sum += diff;
            } else if Some(&diff) < heap.peek() {
                sum -= heap.pop().unwrap();
                sum += diff;
                heap.push(diff);
            }
        }
        heap.len() as i32
    }
}
```

