# Intuition
So as the question states we need to maximize the number of full bags, we can approach this problem in greedy way.

# Approach
1)Take an array which would be storing the difference of capacity of a bag and the initial rocks in it.

2)Then Sort the array (reason being we will first consume the minimum spaces so as to maximize the number ).

3)Reduce the additionalStones counts and move forward in the array.

4)At last calculate the number of zero in the ans array.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Complexity is O(n*log(n)) where n is the size of capacity array.

- Space complexity:
Space Complexity is O(n) where n is the size of capacity ans array we we are using.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumBags(vector<int>& capacity, vector<int>& rocks, int additionalRocks) {
        vector<int> ans;
        for(int i=0;i<capacity.size();i++)
            ans.push_back(capacity[i]-rocks[i]);
        sort(ans.begin(),ans.end());
        int i=0;
        while(i<capacity.size())
        {
            if(additionalRocks<ans[i])
            {
                ans[i]-=additionalRocks;
                additionalRocks=0;
                break;
            }
            else
            {
                additionalRocks-=ans[i];
                ans[i]=0;
            }
            if(additionalRocks<=0)
                break;
            i++;
        }
        int fk=count(ans.begin(),ans.end(),0);
        return fk;
    }
};
```

