# Time Complexity of Algorithm Using priority_queue

The following code uses a priority_queue. 
I have guessed that the time complexity is **O(m * n)**;
**m** being the size of the rocks/capacity array;
**n** being the number of additionalRocks;

My tought was: At worst I'll have to iterate over the whole array decreasing the amount of **additionalRocks** only by one at each time.

Follows the example of worst case:
capacity: 
[2,2,2,2,2]
rocks:    
[1,1,1,1,1]
additionalRocks:
5

My question is:
Can the priority_queue somehow make the time complexity worst?

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumBags(vector<int>& capacity, vector<int>& rocks, int additionalRocks) {
        bool isFull = false;
        int n = rocks.size();
        priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> pq;
        int res = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(capacity[i] == rocks[i]) res++;
            else pq.push(capacity[i] - rocks[i]);
        } 
        while(!pq.empty() && pq.top() <= additionalRocks) {
            res++;
            additionalRocks -= pq.top();
            pq.pop();
        }
        return res;
    }
};

```

